arChildNodes.szComment:
Abasi shares recognition of his aging body and his willingness to offer his heart (literally) to an ancient spirit of his people to see his family protected after his death.
Pronunciation: "Nyah-moy-oh"
Pronunciation "Jee-ohna"

Jiona reinforces that she wishes for her father's company in his final days, not a ritual to an ancient spirit of their ancestors.
Pronunciation: "bah-bah"
Abasi recognises his daugher's concern, but reminds her that there is little he can do to prolong his time with her.
Jiona points at her father's stubborness--playfully comparing it to his warrior skill.
Abasi attempts to lift his daughter's spirits by responding to her jab with a playful retort--saying his stubborness is what keeps his spear steady in his late years.

Abasi requests the player bring him the flowers he needs for the ritual--speaking to it allowing him to awaken his ancestory spirit (Nyamoyo) once more.
Pronunciation: "Dah-moo"
